<TITLE> Rice vows US will keep world pressure on Myanmar </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 WASHINGTON, Dec 21 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Secretary of State Condoleezza Rice on Friday promised renewed efforts at the United Nations and with China to press Myanmar's ruling junta to negotiate with its democratic opposition. Rice said she was concerned that world attention to the former Burma had dissipated since September's bloody crackdown on protests led by Buddhist monks. World leaders criticized the government's actions and the UN tried to promote dialogue. "It's our responsibility, along with others, to try to keep a focus on that effort," Rice told a year-end news conference. "We will return again and again to the Security Council to discuss this issue. We will return again and again to those states that have influence, like China, to move this forward." The top US plomat said Washington wanted the military leaders who have run Myanmar since 1962 to listen to detained democracy leader Aung San Suu Kyi and to end "unacceptable" treatment of the special UN envoy. Ibrahim Gambari, special envoy of UN Secretary General Ban Ki-moon, has visited Myanmar twice since the crackdown, which a recent UN report said killed at least 31 people, more than three times the junta's official toll. Gambari, who visited Washington this week, has held meetings with Suu Kyi and junta leader Than Shwe. But the only concrete result of his visits has been the appointment of another general to act as go-between for the pair. Rice's comments on Friday followed a flurry of actions in Congress on Myanmar, including passage of a bill blocking imports of Myanmar rubies and timber, and a campaign by US lawmakers for a UN arms embargo on the country. Analysts said China is key to a Myanmar resolution because Beijing is the junta's main ally and chief arms supplier. But China, a veto-wielding permanent member of the UN Security Council that has protected Myanmar from UN action in the past, told an EU envoy on Thursday that it would not push for the release of Suu Kyi or other political prisoners. Suu Kyi's National League for Democracy won elections in 1990, but the army refused to hand over power and has detained the Nobel Peace laureate for most of the time since th
